## Verifying Changes

`just verify` is the ground-truth command for both human developers and coding
agents in this project. Coding agents in particular should rely on its
machine-readable output formats rather than scraping pretty stdout.

### Commands

- `just verify` — runs quick + standard tier checks.
- `just verify --quick` — fast iteration; quick tier only.
- `just verify --full` — includes slow tier.
- `just verify --no-cache` — bypass the cache (force re-execution).
- `just verify-clean` — wipe `.verify/` artifacts.

### Output formats

`verify-kit verify --format=<fmt>` accepts `pretty` (default), `json`, `jsonl`,
`junit`, `sarif`, and `otlp`. Regardless of stdout format, every run writes
`.verify/report.json`, `.verify/report.junit.xml`, and `.verify/report.sarif`
to disk for CI / agent consumption. Writes are atomic (tmp file + `os.replace`)
so agents never read partial files.

### JSONL streaming contract

When `--format=jsonl`, each line is a `CheckResult` JSON object except for the
final line, which is the summary:

```json
{"type": "summary", "pass_count": N, "fail_count": N, "skip_count": N, "total": N, "duration_ms": N, "exit_code": N}
```

Agents detect end-of-stream by parsing `type == "summary"`.

### Did-you-mean

Typo'd check ids and unknown CLI options/subcommands trigger a
`did you mean: ...` suggestion before exit.

### Prerequisites & graceful degradation

The recommended bootstrap is `mise install` (installs Python + Node + `just`).
A `make verify` shim is provided for users without `just`. If `just` is missing
at run time, the `just-list.renders` check **skips with a hint** instead of
failing — so `verify-kit verify --quick` succeeds on a freshly-cloned scaffold
*before* `mise install` runs. The `lint.biome` / `format.biome` checks similarly
skip when biome is not locally installed; `verify` is offline-first and will
never call `pnpm dlx` to fetch tools on demand.

### Exit codes

| Code | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| 0    | all checks passed |
| 1    | one or more checks failed |
| 2    | bad input (invalid CLI flag, unknown check id, malformed config) |
| 10   | cache corruption (`.verify/cache.db` unreadable) |
| 11   | required external tool missing (e.g. `uv`) |
| 12   | report write failed (supersedes 1 — missing `.verify/report.*` is higher severity than a check failure) |
| 13   | OTel endpoint configured but unreachable |

## Observability

OpenTelemetry instrumentation ships with verify-kit but is **inert by default**.
The OTel SDK is not imported at all when `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` is unset
(verified by `tests/test_phase2_otel_inert.py` in the verify-kit repo). To
enable tracing, set the endpoint and pick a backend.

### Jaeger via `just trace-up` (default)

```bash
export OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT=http://localhost:4317
just trace-up           # starts Jaeger 1.76.0 all-in-one in Docker
just verify             # spans are emitted to Jaeger
just trace --last       # render the most recent trace as an ASCII waterfall
just trace-down         # stop Jaeger
```

Jaeger UI is at <http://localhost:16686>.

### Non-Docker alternatives

For developers who prefer not to run Docker locally:

1. **[otel-desktop-viewer](https://github.com/CtrlSpice/otel-desktop-viewer)** —
   macOS menubar app; receives OTLP on `4317`/`4318`; shows traces in a browser
   tab at <http://localhost:8000>.
2. **[otel-tui](https://github.com/ymtdzzz/otel-tui)** — terminal-based OTLP
   receiver with an inline waterfall renderer; best for headless / SSH sessions.
3. **[Grafana Tempo](https://grafana.com/docs/tempo/latest/getting-started/)**
   via Docker Compose — overkill for a solo developer; appropriate for teams
   that already run Grafana.

### `docker-compose.observability.yml` (team pattern)

If your team prefers a single Compose file alongside the application stack,
the minimal pattern is:

```yaml
services:
  jaeger:
    image: jaegertracing/all-in-one:1.76.0
    ports:
      - "16686:16686"   # UI
      - "4317:4317"     # OTLP gRPC
      - "4318:4318"     # OTLP HTTP
```

This is functionally equivalent to `just trace-up` and a reasonable substitute
when you want observability infrastructure to live in `docker-compose.yml`
beside the app services.
{% if has_backend %}

When the Backend addon is enabled, the FastAPI app reuses the same Jaeger
endpoint — application traces and verify traces appear together in the UI.
{% endif %}

